name: Yoni Alter
description:
ABOUT YONI ALTER

Yoni Alter is a multimedia artist exploring the threshold between art and design. His vibrantly coloured works segue between the figurative, the abstract, form, and space, always challenging viewers to look twice.Guided by experimentation and semiotics, Yoni passionately seeks new ways of creating visual representations, working across sculpture, painting, print, and digital media.

 

YONI ALTERS EARLY CAREER AND INFLUENCES


Alter studied Art and Design in Jerusalem before completing his MA in Graphic Design at the University of the Arts London. London ceaselessly functions as a source of inspiration for the artist. For example, his debut London show at Kemistry Gallery creatively abstracted London architecture and the surrounding urban landscape. Yoni synthesises sharp silhouettes, bold colouring, and Pop Art iconography, reflecting the seductive creative vibe of London city.

COLLABORATIONS AND DESIGN


Yoni also designs graphic works for iconic brands, with past collaborations including projects with Karl Lagerfeld and Hermes. He is also behind a best-selling merchandise range for Tate. You may have seen his work covering double-decker buses; on a 25m long banner in Shoreditch and on a 25m tall LED tree in Wembley. His art was part of the acclaimed 100 Years of Graphic Design exhibition. Press features include The Guardian, Phaidon, Campaign, The Atlantic, and My Modern Met, to name a few.

name: Fairly
description:
Welcome to my little universe of inspiration and creation! I am a vintage fabric addict and flea market junkie. My etsy shop offers a range of hand-made bags and home accessories, as well as a few clothing items, all designed and sewn by me. As I get enthusiastic about too many lovely things, you may also encounter some favourite flea market finds and a range of beautiful vintage textiles in my shop!

I am no expert seamstress, nor am I a trained designer. However, I have always had a slumbering passion for beautiful textiles (especially colorful ones!) which would awake every once in a while.

The key awakening happened one sunny day at the fleamarket in Old Jaffa: I stumbled upon my first Kantha quilt ever. Fascinated by these hand-stitched, layered and amazingly colourful textiles, I set out to find more of them.

My Kantha quilt (and other textile) passion, combined with some sewing skills (mainly acquired during elementary school sewing lessons), eventually led me to start my own little artisan venture, Fairly.

I started out making Kantha bags and pouches, and from there my creativity evolved to embrace other types of fabrics. I got addicted to South East Asian hill tribe textiles - painstakingly hand-embroidered rainbow baby carriers and wonderful, hand-woven indigo fabric rolls. From there, I moved to gorgeous Guatemalan huipils and Mexican Otomi fabrcis. I am still discovering new, precious textiles, always trying to turn them into special bags or home accessories.

All the while, my passion for Kantha quilts hasn't waned, and I found a production partner in Bangladesh, who creates lovely quilts, baby blankets and scarves for me. My production partner is a Bangladeshi NGO that supports women in need. It helps them make a respectable living by stitching those gorgeous quilts.

Creating things has taught me a lot about myself and about the way of life I would really like to lead. It has taught me respect for material things and their scarcity, as well as appreciation for all things hand-made in our fast-paced world.

This one's a lovely handmade Kantha bag in a very simple style - made from just two pieces of fair trade* Kantha quilt in a blue, black and white pattern, with the reverse side in orange. The bag closes at the top with a vintage button and small Kuchi tassel. You can also wear the bag inside out if you like the reverse side better! The bag is fairly light and comes with no frills, except for one sewn-on pocket. Sewn with organic cotton thread.

Materials: 
vintage kantha quilt, cotton, sari, kantha, organic cotton thread, vintage button, tassel

Measurements:
From bottom to top of strap: about 67cm or 26 inches
Width: about 38cm or 15 inches
Height (without strap): about 33cm 13 inches

Care instructions: hand-wash. The button is made from leather, so I am not sure how well it will hold up when getting wet.

Please bear in mind that the fabrics I use sometimes have small flaws, such as staining, small holes or patched-up areas. Usually, these are not very noticeable, and they often add character to the piece!

*Our newly stitched Kantha products are produced by women in Meherpur, Bangladesh, in cooperation with Tripty Boutique, a socially responsible enterprise. Tripty Boutique is a subsidiary of the NGO Center for Development and Peace, which strives to empower the most vulnerable and at-risk women and children by providing them with a livelihood. By purchasing one of our Kantha products, you directly support a woman in need in Bangladesh. Learn more at www.triptyboutique.com.

Kantha quilts consist of several layers of recycled saris held together by a simple running "Kantha" stitch that is applied row after row and gives the textile its unique, slightly wavy texture. This kind of embroidery is popular with the rural women of Bangladesh and West Bengal. It can take weeks to create one of these wonderful textile pieces, each one of a kind, each carrying the distinct handwriting of its creator's craft(wo)manship.

If you would like to read a little more about Kantha quilts, check out my blog at www.fairlyworn.com/blog !
